s on Charles Darwin, and will occur after Iowa City\'s Darwin Day events from February 21st-23rd. His topic is his research on the evolution of sex.\r\n\r\nProfessor Logsdon\'s research focuses on understanding the molecular natural history of sexual reproduction, focusing specifically on meiosis, the special cell division that allows for sex to proceed. We are studying diverse biological systems that appear, in various ways, to be exceptions to many \"rules\" in sexual biology. Using data gathered from studies of these various organisms, we ask and attempt answer some of the following questions: When did sex and meiosis arise? How and from what prior function(s) did sex and Meiosis derive? How has sex subsequently evolved? Can sex and meiosis be lost? ','Sex, cells: Origins and Natural History of Meiosis','','publish','open','closed','','secsi-general-meeting-2014-02-25','','','2014-02-24 21:21:58','2014-02-25 03:21:58','',0,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/events/secsi-general-meeting-2014-02-25/',0,'event','',0),(239,3,'2014-02-03 05:05:38','2014-02-03 05:05:38','','SecSI General Meeting','','publish','open','open','','secsi-general-meeting-2014-03-04','','','2014-02-03 05:05:38','2014-02-03 05:05:38','',0,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/events/secsi-general-meeting-2014-03-04/',0,'event','',0),(240,3,'2014-02-03 05:05:38','2014-02-03 05:05:38','','SecSI General Meeting','','publish','open','open','','secsi-general-meeting-2014-03-11','','','2014-02-03 05:05:38','2014-02-03 05:05:38','',0,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/events/secsi-general-meeting-2014-03-11/',0,'event','',0),(241,2,'2014-02-03 17:53:42','2014-02-03 17:53:42','[promoslider id=\"home-page-slider\"]\r\n<hr>\r\n<h1 style=\'border-bottom: solid black 2px;\'>Latest SecSI Posts</h1>\r\n[miniloop number_posts=6 before_items=\"<ul class=\'home-page-ul\'>\" after_items=\"</ul>\"]\r\n<li class=\"[class]\"><p><h3><a href=\"[url]\">[title]</a></h3>\r\n<p>[excerpt wlength=75 space_between=1 