elling discoveries in astronomy, geology, or biology that would speak to the existence of a god or gods. Or for that matter, anything we could rightly consider as evidence. Which, you know, should be what you\'re looking for when somebody is trying to convince you to dedicate your life, income, and effort to said belief.\r\n\r\nAnyway, if you\'re looking for some entertainment tonight, I think you can watch it here, tonight: <a href=\"http://debatelive.org/\">http://debatelive.org/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"620\"]<a href=\"http://www.vocativ.com/02-2014/creationism-drinking-game/\"><img title=\"Bill Nye vs Ken Ham Debate Bingo\" alt=\"\" src=\"http://media.vocativ.com/photos/2014/02/bingo_lg23986160145.png\" width=\"620\" height=\"915\" /></a> They forgot, \"we need to teach both sides of the debate!\"[/caption]\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vocativ.com/02-2014/creationism-drinking-game/\">http://www.vocativ.com/02-2014/creationism-drinking-game/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhile I\'m on the topic. I\'d like to stress that, even though Bill Nye vs Ken Ham is more entertainment that it is...academic, creationism is still a serious issue in this country. This map apparently shows which public schools are using your tax money to insert Christian, religious fundamental teachings into the science classroom. Don\'t believe me? Check out this powerpoint appropriated from an *actual* 21st century classroom.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/file/d/0B-NEiXUyP5AecXpuT1JGYk5VZW8/edit\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow nofollow\">https://docs.google.com/file/d/0B-NEiXUyP5AecXpuT1JGYk5VZW8/edit</a>\r\n\r\nIf you live in the unfortunate states of Kentucky (home to Creation Museum), Louisiana, or...worst of all...Texas, you should be particularly horrified.\r\n\r\nThe bottom line is: only science belongs in the classroom. Religious beliefs should and must stay in the church, away from the minds of impressionable children.\r\n\r\n[capti