\'s current, on-the-record stance for each issue, and a thorough description of the criticisms presented by those looking at the book from an objective standpoint.\r\n\r\nI recommend starting with the Book of Mormon problems page, and selecting from the given issues on the right side nav.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Mormonthink.com','','inherit','open','open','','325-revision-v1','','','2014-02-08 19:51:29','2014-02-09 01:51:29','',325,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/325-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(327,2,'2014-02-08 20:04:15','0000-00-00 00:00:00','[miniloop','Blog','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-02-08 20:04:15','2014-02-09 02:04:15','',0,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/?page_id=327',0,'page','',0),(330,3,'2014-02-10 20:37:27','2014-02-11 02:37:27','<p> I recently replied to a post on facebook.  Out of respect for the person, I will not include the original quote.  However, the post mainly claimed that there is a difference between \"observable science\" and \"historical science\" (referring to the debate between Bill Nye and Ken Ham).  The person then went on to claim that evolution is simply a guess about how organisms came to be and is essentially untestable or unverifiable.  Furthermore, the person continued on to claim that evolution has not been proven or ever observed. </p>\r\n\r\n<p> I ultimately decided to respond to this post.  I did not want to seem rude, as my intention was to hopefully clarify this issue.  (Make no mistake.  The person who posted this is a kind person, so they should be treated with respect.  If you comment, please keep this in mind.)  Here is my response: </p>\r\n\r\n<p> \"I sincerely hope you don\'t mind me commenting... (If so, then I apologize. Also, I tend to type a lot, so I apologize if the length of this turns out to be long... I\'ll try to keep it as concise as possible especially since I myself have homework to do!) However, I think I can possibly clarify this. There\'s a reason why scientists do not recognize \"observable science\" and \"historical science\" as two different categories. For one, all science is based on the scientific method (<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FScientific_method&amp;h=gAQFliX6C&amp;enc=AZOjzwbUHe09xtAk-yW-w7cV67-x_l5cR5ns1LBIprfc6o7-V7o54HN7XQTxUJfkPDnSm4mv5UGxq2GAsTWeu0J75gImgZVb4Ouz1L_6m263fFZQ484ZtNy3UF4M_MdwQkfYxyTlg7WbddFtflL9Ogyi&amp;s=1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_method</a>). Unfortunately, this process is generally misunderstood. Theories (<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FScientific_theory&amp;h=dAQGNyCgR&amp;enc=AZMjomT1CKivOMKZAMQ6r185wJoSzur73mgvnl9yl6Ek9EhUk8lG9tn8gKK32aAWOD5ProQcYkzd5IA-TIKq25ecZI4AHBff4vYhdzU3Z_-jSQK7nftGKK90lhxW1PjHdXwG8XfrdwRJLUmiN_MTQR1O&amp;s=1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_theory</a>) are probably one of the most important aspects of the scientific endeavor. The goal of science is not to find \"absolute truth\", but rather to build a model that we are highly confident can predict the future accurately. </p>\r\n\r\n<p> Why are theories so important? First of all theories help us to make sense of any factual data that we have already acquired. Any theory should agree with current known facts about the universe. However, how can we be confident that this theory accurately describes nature? Since science is always adventuring into the unknown, how do we know our explanations are accurate? We need a way to build *confidence* in our model. We call it confidence instead of certainty because, by the nature of the process, we have to admit we can\'t be absolutely certain. However, if the model correctly conforms to what we observe in nature *before* we knew about them, then this gives an indication that the model (theory) as a whole is correct. (Modifications may be necessary.) The reason that this builds our confidence is because most likely, had the theory been an inaccurate model of reality, we would have found some piece of evidence that would contradict the ideas that the theory is based upon. </p>\r\n\r\n<p> Let\'s take an example. The Standard Model. This is a particle physics theory. (<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FStandard_Model&amp;h=eAQF79-PA&amp;enc=AZNNmXDQH1TGqUNvYrH-WaW-XzuDqRbJRB_1SNKMxw02PwiIX6Qi68Uq4yhD9k_0DqchQexo95VGMlzDgCIaIxj6tq3Edg_g5FVasn2u18cecoFaQyqfPnF4scxes8JtxGFLkIQvggfwy5skdpEwouq6&amp;s=1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_Model</a>) This theory was formulated around the 1970\'s. (I don\'t recall exactly.) However, it became apparent that there were gaps that were unaccounted for. As such, physicists were able to hypothesize the existence of several particles, one of which is the well-known Higgs boson. It should be noted that we had no idea the Higgs even existed when this theory was formulated. But if the theory was to be an accurate model of reality, we had to find a particle like the Higgs boson. Per the predictions, we were able to go out and look for this specific particle. As most people now know, we have found it. This lends support to the Standard Model. There may need to be corrections here and there to the theory, but overall our confidence is high in the theory due to its success in predicting many different particles that we didn\'t know even existed! If it would have made one prediction wrong, a new theory would need to emerge. </p>\r\n\r\n<p> Let\'s take another example, and compare. Evolution. (In particular, the idea of \"common descent\".) The idea behind evolution was proposed in the 1800s, before we knew anything about genetics. As many people know, the entire concept behind evolution is that of \"common descent\". That is, all life is related by a common ancestor. From this, biologists constructed a \"tree of life\" based on things such as characteristics, fossil evidence, and other things. (Before genetics.) While the theory of evolution was correct in its predictions before genetics, I will not focus on those. </p>\r\n\r\n<p> Now, the question is, what did evolutionary theory predict correctly? In each instance, evolutionary theory could have been *falsified immediately* if it was incorrect in any of its predictions. (And as some of you may have guessed, it has been correct in every single one.) Let\'s examine a few of these. Shall we? </p>\r\n\r\n<p> One example is endogenous retroviruses. (For those that\'d rather watch a video...: <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3Dqh7OclPDN_s&amp;h=uAQE3nx_8&amp;enc=AZOQ5Iv1Xvwi66MYaUgMoTZMJYm09FBqqGVjacM5eKzkpALNSot5Sd23B_uhCD9OdnMq8HxYSlfUuvVDWsaeHMzziFc7BCDDOO2cBM6UIatROcySJSY15BW5htQngIgU4deYPKQMIcLnHK4xW7fKqwNU&amp;s=1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qh7OclPDN_s</a>) If you\'ll excuse me borrowing from a source (As it\'d be rather tedious for me to type this up myself:<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.talkorigins.org%2Ffaqs%2Fcomdesc%2Fsection4.html%23retroviruses&amp;h=eAQF79-PA&amp;enc=AZMUVvq-Od0y8LYGbVYVctljknQRrAveSnvOqCsqn2xFjZcLzLprygIwMfATFGIIvxyGuy1PmHpT4A09U6MIBXgjF7QuPB1KOUFmtc12_CKXuOhJu9gtJql3A4Cj9IpBRZxm1rbGkvSzpIj2EnXitHLB&amp;s=1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/comdesc/section4.html#retroviruses</a>):  </p>\r\n\r\n<p> \"Endogenous retroviruses provide yet another example of molecular sequence evidence for universal common descent. Endogenous retroviruses are molecular remnants of a past parasitic viral infection. Occasionally, copies of a retrovirus genome are found in its host\'s genome, and these retroviral gene copies are called endogenous retroviral sequences. Retroviruses (like the AIDS virus or HTLV1, which causes a form of leukemia) make a DNA copy of their own viral genome and insert it into their host\'s genome. If this happens to a germ line cell (i.e. the sperm or egg cells) the retroviral DNA will be inherited by descendants of the host. Again, this process is rare and fairly random, so finding retrogenes in identical chromosomal positions of two different species indicates common ancestry.\" </p>\r\n\r\n<p> Okay. How could this falsify evolution? </p>\r\n\r\n<p> \"Potential Falsification:</p>\r\n\r\n<p> It would make no sense, macroevolutionarily, if certain other mammals (e.g. dogs, cows, platypi, etc.), had these same retrogenes in the exact same chromosomal locations. For instance, it would be incredibly unlikely for dogs to also carry the three HERV-K insertions that are unique to humans, as shown in the upper right of Figure 4.4.1, since none of the other primates have these retroviral sequences.\" </p>\r\n\r\n<p> This is an interesting prediction. It seems fairly easy to falsify evolution. Take the above predicted hierarchy from evolution, and see if there are any ERV insertions in places that do not make any sense. For example, if humans shared an ERV insertion with mice, but the other primates did not have this insertions in the same place, this would falsify the idea of common descent. However, we *never* find this. Essentially what this is saying is, as you get \"closer\" on the tree of life as predicted by evolution, the number of shared ERV insertions increase. It\'s actually more than this! If you took a human and a mouse, looked for ERVs they have in common, then this implies that we have an ERV insertion in the exact same place with other closer relatives (like other primates). Distant relatives sharing an ERV implies that closer relatives have that *exact* ERV in the *exact* same place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p> Evolution correctly predicted this outcome, which is incredibly unlikely to happen on its own. This lends support to the idea of common descent. Notice in this piece of evidence, we can convince ourselves without even having to directly observe this entire process happening. Assuming that this process happens and then seeing if we can falsify what logically follows from assuming that position, helps us lend credibility to an idea. This is *exactly* the same process as outlined above for the Standard Model. In fact, take the confirmation of any widely accepted theory, and the process of confirmation is exactly the same. Create a theory, make predictions, and try to falsify it. </p>\r\n\r\n<p> In the interest of shortening this comment (haha!), I\'ll just list other things I happen to know of where evolution has made the correction prediction on what to find. In every instance, each piece of evidence could have falsified evolution. Here: 1) Fusion of the 2nd chromosome, 2) Pseudogenes, 3) Ring species (This in particular is good to debunk the idea of \"kinds\"), 4) Proteins (<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DmA7BE3mEb64&amp;h=4AQEo_spY&amp;enc=AZPqWISH-CWVYB0D3-7AFPtZCPJv1WfWX8kSAbZ_0kqo8vPVsaLXUyz8YBe_xmRfVnETqGlHsAWKiEysrXQB5JwCGj2PMKiD6TvHudLKn-lEJjnSv_LqJGRMetjp4L-Hu0Z95qn2TFGb4tHEeykHhdUZ&amp;s=1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mA7BE3mEb64</a>), as well as others. We should ask ourselves. How has this theory stood strong with every test we\'ve thrown at it? We could have falsified it time after time after time again, but we have not. At what point do we finally say, \"Okay, this theory seems to be an accurate model of reality. It drives discovery and it correctly accounts for everything we know, and everything we continue to figure out.\" This is what happens with every theory. Scientists become convinced a theory is an accurate model of reality, based on its *predictive power*. This is why scientists always talk about predictive power, because it builds our confidence in its accuracy. This is why scientists are convinced evolution is an accurate model of reality. </p>\r\n\r\n<p> I apologize for the length and if anyone read this, thanks! I TRIED to be brief, but I\'m told absolutely terrible at that. Yay science! (Now to get back to work on homework!)</p>\r\n\r\n<p> Thank you.\" </p>','\"Observational Science\" vs. \"Historical Science\"','','publish','open','open','','observational-science-vs-historical-science','','','2014-02-10 22:00:07','2014-02-11 04:00:07','',0,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/?p=330',0,'post','',0),(331,3,'2014-02-10 20:37:27','2014-02-11 02:37:27','I recently replied to a post on facebook.  Out of respect for the person, I will not include the original quote.  However, the post mainly claimed that there is a difference between \"observable science\" and \"historical science\" (referring to the debate between Bill Nye and Ken Ham).  The person then went on to claim that evolution is simply a guess about how organisms came to be and is essentially untestable or unverifiable.  Furthermore, the person continued on to claim that evolution has not been proven or ever observed.\r\n\r\nI ultimately decided to respond to this post.  I did not want to seem rude, as my intention was to hopefully clarify this issue.  (Make no mistake.  The person who posted this is a kind person, so they should be treated with respect.  If you comment, please keep this in mind.)  Here is my response:\r\n\r\n\"I sincerely hope you don\'t mind me commenting... (If so, then I apologize. Also, I tend to type a lot, so I apologize if the length of this turns out to be long... I\'ll try to keep it as concise as possible especially since I myself have homework to do!) However, I think I can possibly clarify this. There\'s a reason why scientists do not recognize \"observable science\" and \"historical science\" as two different categories. For one, all science is based on the scientific method (<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FScientific_method&amp;h=gAQFliX6C&amp;enc=AZOjzwbUHe09xtAk-yW-w7cV67-x_l5cR5ns1LBIprfc6o7-V7o54H