heory, make predictions, and try to falsify it.\r\n\r\nIn the interest of shortening this comment (haha!), I\'ll just list other things I happen to know of where evolution has made the correction prediction on what to find. In every instance, each piece of evidence could have falsified evolution. Here: 1) Fusion of the 2nd chromosome, 2) Pseudogenes, 3) Ring species (This in particular is good to debunk the idea of \"kinds\"), 4) Proteins (<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DmA7BE3mEb64&amp;h=4AQEo_spY&amp;enc=AZPqWISH-CWVYB0D3-7AFPtZCPJv1WfWX8kSAbZ_0kqo8vPVsaLXUyz8YBe_xmRfVnETqGlHsAWKiEysrXQB5JwCGj2PMKiD6TvHudLKn-lEJjnSv_LqJGRMetjp4L-Hu0Z95qn2TFGb4tHEeykHhdUZ&amp;s=1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mA7BE3mEb64</a>), as well as others. We should ask ourselves. How has this theory stood strong with every test we\'ve thrown at it? We could have falsified it time after time after time again, but we have not. At what point do we finally say, \"Okay, this theory seems to be an accurate model of reality. It drives discovery and it correctly accounts for everything we know, and everything we continue to figure out.\" This is what happens with every theory. Scientists become convinced a theory is an accurate model of reality, based on its *predictive power*. This why scientists always talk about predictive power, because it builds our confidence in its accuracy. This is why scientists are convinced evolution is an accurate model of reality.\r\n\r\nI apologize for the length and if anyone read this, thanks! I TRIED to be brief, but I\'m told absolutely terrible at that. Yay science! (Now to get back to work on homework!)\r\n\r\nThank you.\"','\"Observational Science\" vs. \"Historical Science\"','','inherit','open','open','','330-revision-v1','','','2014-02-10 20:37:27','2014-02-11 02:37:27','',330,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/330-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(332,2,'2014-02-