rtion with mice, but the other primates did not have this insertions in the same place, this would falsify the idea of common descent. However, we *never* find this. Essentially what this is saying is, as you get \"closer\" on the tree of life as predicted by evolution, the number of shared ERV insertions increase. It\'s actually more than this! If you took a human and a mouse, looked for ERVs they have in common, then this implies that we have an ERV insertion in the exact same place with other closer relatives (like other primates). Distant relatives sharing an ERV implies that closer relatives have that *exact* ERV in the *exact* same place.\n\nEvolution correctly predicted this outcome, which is incredibly unlikely to happen on its own. This lends support to the idea of common descent. Notice in this piece of evidence, we can convince ourselves without even having to directly observe this entire process happening. Assuming that this process happens and then seeing if we can falsify what logically follows from assuming that position, helps us lend credibility to an idea. This is *exactly* the same process as outlined above for the Standard Model. In fact, take the confirmation of any widely accepted theory, and the process of confirmation is exactly the same. Create a theory, make predictions, and try to falsify it.\n\nIn the interest of shortening this comment (haha!), I\'ll just list other things I happen to know of where evolution has made the correction prediction on what to find. In every instance, each piece of evidence could have falsified evolution. Here: 1) Fusion of the 2nd chromosome, 2) Pseudogenes, 3) Ring species (This in particular is good to debunk the idea of \"kinds\"), 4) Proteins (<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3DmA7BE3mEb64&amp;h=4AQEo_spY&amp;enc=AZPqWISH-CWVYB0D3-7AFPtZCPJv1WfWX8kSAbZ_0kqo8vPVsaLXUyz8YBe_xmRfVnETqGlHsAWKiEysrXQB5JwCGj2PMKiD6TvHudLKn-lEJjnSv_LqJGRMetjp4L-Hu0Z95qn2TFGb4tHEeykHhdUZ&amp;s=1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mA7BE3mEb64</a>), as well as others. We should ask ourselves. How has this theory stood strong with every test we\'ve thrown at it? We could have falsified it time after time after time again, but we have not. At what point do we finally say, \"Okay, this theory seems to be an accurate model of reality. It drives discovery and it correctly accounts for everything we know, and everything we continue to figure out.\" This is what happens with every theory. Scientists become convinced a theory is an accurate model of reality, based on its *predictive power*. This why scientists always talk about predictive power, because it builds our confidence in its accuracy. This is why scientists are convinced evolution is an accurate model of reality.\n\nI apologize for the length and if anyone read this, thanks! I TRIED to be brief, but I\'m told absolutely terrible at that. Yay science! (Now to get back to work on homework!)\n\nThank you.\"','\"Observational Science\" vs. \"Historical Science\"','','inherit','open','open','','330-autosave-v1','','','2014-02-10 20:52:49','2014-02-11 02:52:49','',330,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/330-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(335,3,'2014-02-10 20:53:31','2014-02-11 02:53:31','<p> I recently replied to a post on facebook.  Out of respect for the person, I will not include the original quote.  However, the post mainly claimed that there is a difference between \"observable science\" and \"historical science\" (referring to the debate between Bill Nye and Ken Ham).  The person then went on to claim that evolution is simply a guess about how organisms came to be and is essentially untestable or unverifiable.  Furthermore, the person continued on to claim that evolution has not been proven or ever observed. </p>\r\n\r\n<p> I ultimately decided to respond to this post.  I did not want to seem rude, as my intention was to hopefully clarify this issue.  