nThe unspoken assumption is \'people of faith\' answer to a different government.','\"Imposing\" Secular Values on People of Faith','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-04-05 21:30:10','2014-04-06 02:30:10','',0,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/?p=449',0,'post','',0),(450,2,'2014-04-05 21:30:10','2014-04-06 02:30:10','Rhetoric of Catholics to treat government as if it somehow entirely removed from society. Government shouldn\'t tell me what to do, blah, blah, blah, etc. What they seem happily ignoring is that America, our government included, is the 15th most democratic country in the world. I understand that some may see the number 15 as something to be ashamed of, rather than proud. The thinking comes from the American-centric atitudes about the world. The truth is, of the 196 countries in the world, that puts is in the top 13%.\r\n\r\nWhat this means is that here, more than 77% of the rest of the world, our government IS a representation of our population. Of course some demographics are more represented than others.\r\n\r\nThe unspoken assumption is \'people of faith\' answer to a different government.','\"Imposing\" Secular Values on People of Faith','','inherit','open','open','','449-revision-v1','','','2014-04-05 21:30:10','2014-04-06 02:30:10','',449,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/449-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(451,2,'2014-04-08 18:14:37','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Sample','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-04-08 18:14:37','2014-04-08 23:14:37','',0,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/?p=451',0,'post','',0),(455,2,'2014-04-14 12:52:54','0000-00-00 00:00:00','“Selfishness is not living as one wishes to live, it is asking others to live as one wishes to live. And unselfishness is letting other people\'s lives alone, not interfering with them. Selfishness always aims at creating around it an absolute uniformity of type. Unselfishness recognises infinite variety of type as a delightful thing, accepts it, acquiesces in it, enjoys it. It is not selfish to think for oneself. A man who does not think for himself does not think at all. It is grossly selfish to require of one\'s neighbour that he should think in the same way, and hold the same opinions. Why should he? If he can think, he will probably think differently. If he cannot think, it is monstrous to require thought of any kind from him. A red rose is not selfish because it wants to be a red rose. It would be horribly selfish if it wanted all the other flowers in the garden to be both red and roses.”\r\n\r\n- Oscar Wilde, The Soul of Man and Prison Writings\r\n\r\nWhat an applicable quote for our day! It seems that since the inception of the United States, and with it, our secular democracy, our greatest hope has been for nothing more than an individual to assert his or her self in the public domain without fear of being left poorer in body, spirit, or economy. Wilde asserts the value of this marketplace of individuals, where each person is viewed as intrinsically valuable, bringing a unique take on life due to the myriad forces that shape a person and also his or her thoughts. As Voltaire said, \"I do not agree with what you have to say, but I\'ll defend to the death your right to say it.\" This sentiment lies at the heart of any debate that doesn\'t end in blood and gore; it\'s the reason that each party can leave a disagreement with their heads still attached to their respective shoulders. This, as we\'re all vaguely aware, is not the standard in all places.\r\n\r\nWith that being said, it seems that we should all pat ourselves on the back each time we come away from a confrontation without gutting our opponents. Not only because it\'s a sets us apart from our primitive ancestors, but because it sets us apart from those individuals that, for one reason or another, disregard this principle to this day. But why, if humans are equally evolved, why do some still resort to violence to press their point? Is it impossible to say? Or is it possible to say, but perhaps not without infringing on the aforementioned principle of inclusivity.\r\n\r\nIt brings up the deeper question: what constitutes respect for diversity? Can diversity be exploited to protect the detracting elements of society? On a societal level, we make laws that affect everybody. When does respect for one group\'s ideals infringe on the ideals of another group in the realm of law? Wilde seems to say here that it is selfish to force others to look, think, and presumably, behave the same as you. I agree. Yet, is that still true if the other is systematically harming the other flowers in the garden? By systematically I mean, based on a system, which is based on an idea, which is the very thing Voltaire and Wilde would see preserved on all accounts.\r\n\r\nIt seems to me that on an individual level, Voltaire, Wilde, and the parade of intellectuals who champion respect for the diversity of people are absolutely correct. Nobody should be judged for their dress, race, gender, sexuality, or any other attribute that makes them a little different than other flowers in the garden. The ideal world is one where you would be content coming into it as any combination of attributes, be that race, socio-economic status, or gender. Where the playing field is level, and your birth doesn\'t define your destiny. But perhaps that\'s where we should conclude our obligation of respect.\r\n\r\nThe ideas people hold are tied very closely to their identity. This is particularly true when it comes to religion. Any religion is, after all, just a system of ideas about the \'true\' nature of currently unknowable things. Each religion posits different answers to questions that seem vital to the operation and maintenance of a life. In essence, each one gives different directions about how to behave, based on a host of truth claims that one must accept as true in order to claim membership.\r\n\r\nYou\'ve heard these truth-claims before, but perhaps you\'ve never stopped to wonder if they  are viable. The most classic truth-claim is that a human-like creator god, at some point in time be it billions of years ago or as recent as 6,000 years ago, spawned the universe and earth as we know today, from absolute nothingness. From this truth-claim, religious leaders (mostly men) have devised entire ecosystems of truth-claims regarding morality, ethics, history, and let us not forget...<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metaphysics\">metaphysics</a>.\r\n\r\nThese truth-claim ecosystems are carefully engineered by theologians to be free of contradiction and hypocrisy. If one thing is declared to be true, it should not imply a contradiction of any of the other truth-claims made by the same religion.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFrom   sexual behavior, what foods and what materials are proper to use, what the best way to dress, talk, play, and work is, and of course, what happens to the individual after (and sometimes before) life on earth.\r\nAbout associated with said individuals, is not worthy of the same level of reverence, if it brings tangible harm to others.','','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-04-14 12:52:54','2014-04-14 17:52:54','',0,'http://secularstudents.org.uiowa.edu/?p=455',0,'post','',0),(456,2,'2014-04-14 12:52:42','2014-04-14 17:52:42','“Selfishness is not living as one wishes to live, it is asking others to live as one wishes to live. And unselfishness is letting other people\'s lives alone, not interfering with them. Selfishness always aims at creating around it an absolute uniformity of type. Unselfishness recognises infinite variety of type as a delightful thing, accepts it, acquiesces in it, enjoys it. It is not selfish to think for oneself. A man who does not think for himself does not think at all. It is grossly selfish to require of one\'s neighbour that he should think in the same way, and hold the same opinions. Why should he? If he can think, he will probably think differently. If he cannot think, it is monst