nWhat an applicable quote for our day! It seems that since the inception of the United States, and with it, our secular democracy, our greatest hope has been for nothing more than an individual to assert his or her self in the public domain without fear of being left poorer in body, spirit, or economy. Wilde asserts the value of this marketplace of individuals, where each person is viewed as intrinsically valuable, bringing a unique take on life due to the myriad forces that shape a person and also his or her thoughts. As Voltaire said, \"I do not agree with what you have to say, but I\'ll defend to the death your right to say it.\" This sentiment lies at the heart of any debate that doesn\'t end in blood and gore; it\'s the reason that each party can leave a disagreement with their heads still attached to their respective shoulders. This, as we\'re all vaguely aware, is not the standard in all places.\r\n\r\nWith that being said, it seems that we should all pat ourselves on the back each time we come away from a confrontation without gutting our opponents. Not only because it\'s a sets us apart from our primitive ancestors, but because it sets us apart from those individuals that, for one reason or another, disregard this principle to this day. But why, if humans are equally evolved, why do some still resort to violence to press their point? Is it impossible to say? Or is it possible to say, but perhaps not without infringing on the aforementioned principle of inclusivity.\r\n\r\nIt brings up the deeper question: what constitutes respect for diversity? Can diversity be exploited to protect the detracting elements of society? On a societal level, we make laws that affect everybody. When does respect for one group\'s ideals infringe on the ideals of another group in the realm of law? Wilde seems to say here that it is selfish to force others to look, think, and presumably, behave the same as you. I agree. Yet, is that still true if the other is systematically harming